			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Part 2 of the comprehensive bard issue list discussion is up.<a name="54382"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 30 04 1:09 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">IMO, just keep one single list (like Tremelo is already doing). As soon as an issue on the list gets taken care of, strike it off and add another issue. Simple, short, sweet, and to-the-point. </span></blockquote> 
<br />
Make no mistake, I am ALL ABOUT what Tremelo is doing.  The voting is extremely important for filling the top 10 list and for making priority decions in the short term.
<br />

<br />
That being said, how should we determine which new items and issues get added?  Sure, we can vote on them, but we are in a position right now where no-one understands all the issues.  Having read through dozens of bard issue threads, I still don't understand all our issues, and I think I'm probably one of the better-read bards out there.  My list isn't a top 10.  It is an attempt at an all-encompassing bard issues list.
<br />

<br />
What I'm trying to do is help us as a community understand what our issues are, how we want them solved, and how important each one is in comparison to the other issues.
<br />

<br />
What I am trying to do is something that takes a lot of time and work: establish a consensus.  It's a hard thing to do, because when it comes to bards, no-one is playing with the full deck.  There are too many play styles, too many levels of play, and too many aspects of gameplay that need to be investigated for all of our issues to be genuinely understood.
<br />

<br />
Tremelo's list is simple, but it is not thorough, structured, or supported by facts.  It is good for what is needed short-term: quick decisions on what to add to our top 10.  I want to help the bard community come to an informed consensus about our class issues, instead of the opinionated ignorance that seems to be dominating the vast majority of most class definition forums.
<br />

<br />
I think I will indeed add the bugs as part F in my second draft.  My issues draft is already too big for 1 post; may as well bring in the bugs.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
